The paper discusses distributed algorithms for dynamic networks, which falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The use of biological processes as inspiration suggests a possible connection to Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) or Social and Information Networks (cs.SI). The focus on measuring dynamic changes recovery performance and proposing a new metric suggests a possible connection to Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) or Machine Learning (cs.LG).
